After 25 loaves of focaccia and experimenting differently each time, I think I’ve figured it out! I’ve been so addicted because baking bread is another way for me to use my hands and bring joy to myself and others. I realized I can’t live without baking and art. Plus who doesn’t love bread? 

✨Measure 4 cups of BREAD flour in a bowl. Mix in 2 tsp active dry yeast and 2 tsp salt. Have 2.25 cups of filtered lukewarm water ready. Gradually mix 1/2 cup water at a time into the flour mixture.  By last 1/2 cup, use hands to mix dough until just combined. DO NOT OVER MIX. dough will feel scraggly and bumpy. (This is a no knead recipe). 
✨Coat base of BPA FREE container with olive oil. Place the dough in container.
✨Drizzle 2 TBSP of olive oil on top of the dough. Take the edges of the dough and fold inward to the center, repeating 6-8 times all around dough.
Let dough sit at room temperature with the lid for 30-45 minutes. Fold dough like above. 
✨Repeat this proving and folding process 2 more times, for total proving time of of 1.5 hours to 2 hrs. dough will be pillowy by third time and more than doubled in size.
✨ Place dough in fridge to prove for 12-72 hours. 
ON DAY OF BAKING:  coat 9”x13” pan generously with olive oil. Transfer dough onto pan. 
✨Let dough prove at room temperature for 1.5 hours; cover with tea towel.
✨After 1.5 hours, dough should have doubled in size. Spread dough out gently to fit pan and take all four sides and fold into the center.  Turn the dough over so smooth side is up. 
✨Prove again for 1.5 hours, then fold like before. 
✨Preheat oven to 425 degrees F. 
✨Prove for another 40 min to an hour. (Total time proving is 2-4 hours room temperature depending where you live) 
After the dough has proved for the last time, it is doubled in size. It’s time to dimple!
✨Drizzle olive oil on top.  Dip fingers into bowl of olive oil and using all your fingers, dimple the dough by sticking your fingers into the dough until it reaches the bottom.  If your yeast is working, you will see gas bubbles form on top.
✨Put your desired toppings on top. Drizzle with a bit more olive oil.
✨Bake for 35 min, let cool, and enjoy!

2022 has been a year of exhilarating fun and many firsts. Looking back, I am proud of what I accomplished, and I have so much energy and excitement to tackle the new year! Reflecting back, here’s some memorable highlights: 
✨I painted 100 gouache 2”x2” thumbnails for @stanprokopenko which was incredibly fun. I challenged myself to paint a lot of city scapes that I don’t usually do.
✨With the help of my amazing friend Janna van Vliet @misstutje who singlehandedly designed my entire book, I published my second book Tiny Big Worlds! The making of this book had been on my mind since 2020, but if it wasn’t for her, I don’t think this book would have been produced. 
✨I was invited to the LPAPA plein air Invitational @lpapamembers for the first time this year, and had such a blast painting and meeting new artists!! I also did my first big nocturne! 
✨I met Marco Bucci @bucciblog for the first time in person at Lightbox!! We tabled next to each other AND taught a workshop! It was also really cool to meet fans who told me they enjoyed my YT videos :) 
✨I had the opportunity to go to Mandurah, Australia to teach two master classes in gouache for @pleinairdownunder . I also met Leon Holmes @leonholmesfineart for the first time after he had taken my gouache mentorship, and to see his paintings in person was just amazing! 
✨I did an oil painting this year which I am still proud of, and it is the first oil painting of mine that was accepted into the 111th CAC Gold Medal Exhibition. 
✨I got to work at two of my dream studios, Cartoon Saloon and Marvel Studios ( still there) on two beautiful TV shows with two awesome teams. 
✨I got over my fear of baking bread, and got obsessed with baking focaccia.
✨I am still with my guy @jhooperphotography who is truly the biggest supporter of all my dreams, and has made so many of my ideas possible. I have a loving family who are all healthy.  My dad suffered from a subdural hematoma earlier this year, but I am glad to say he recovered. His mental strength and positivity is inspirational. 
✨I was handpicked by @keith.the.painter to teach the ultimate online digital painting mentorship in 2023 at @sentientacademy ! I am soo excited for this!

New year, new painting. Here are some black and white exploration thumbnails for a huge 30”x40” oil painting commission featuring the Berserkjahraun Lava Fields in Iceland. I wish I could have actually visited this place because it looks stunning. 
.
A goal for me is to really focus more on the exploration process and not rush to the actual painting. I find that better planning means saving time and heart ache. This is quite a challenge for me because I’m very impatient 😂…. and I often get too excited and rush into things emotionally. After listening to @dibbleart and @t._allen_lawson talk about their creative processes for their oil paintings on the @theundrapedartist I was so inspired to learn how they use color charts, photos, and sketches to create their final paintings. At this point, I have no Idea how this painting will turn out and I don’t have a super clear vision like I usually do, but maybe that’s the most exciting part.

Does working with colors throw you off? If you are finding that colors are really daunting to work with in gouache when starting out, I suggest working with a limited palette of ultramarine, yellow ochre or burnt sienna, and white! Stripping down your colors lets you focus more on value relationships and temperature shifts. 
Extra challenge: use the 1” brush to practice carving out big graphic shapes before working into details! These 2”x2” paintings were all done with the limited palette and 1” brush.

✨check out my video on YouTube!✨ if you’re every wondering how to approach a limited palette gouache painting, I have a video on YouTube that shows you how I tackle it from start to finish! This 6”x6” gouache plein air painting remains one of my favorites today. It’s the kind where it might not be an audience win but it’s personal to me. I had walked by those trees in Poland soo many times before I decided to paint it, and when I plopped down on the bench to paint it just flowed out. It was one of those rare zen moments you never forget because you didn’t fight with your painting 😆
I purposely wanted to have minimal contrast between the trees and the background. I loved the purple tinted atmosphere and how the shadows of the birches almost melted into the bg. We are always usually searching for value contrast, but sometimes it’s the subtle color temperature contrasts that can make a painting sing. 

I can wait to share this in my upcoming workshop in Seville Spain with @lagaleriaroja . It’s one of my favorite things to notice now and capture.

How to Create CONTRAST in your Painting WITHOUT VALUE
https://youtu.be/r7hktsopz08

What happens when you’re faced with a scenario where you don’t have a lot of value contrast? It’s about getting good at training your eyes to capture the subtle hue shifts of similar value to create temperature contrast in your painting. That’s what I talk about in this YouTube video. 

This is a concept that took me years to realize when I started gouache, and I thought I always needed to search for value contrast. If there was none, the painting felt boring! Good thing for us artists, there are more tools in your visual toolbox besides utilizing value contrast to create interest in your painting.

I also learned that snow is VERY hard to paint (for me- I’m a CA girl!) Too saturated and it feels like candy. You gotta get those subtle balance of grays and lovely shadow baby blues just right.

Here is my final 18”x18” gouache piece titled “Daring Greatly.” I’m not sure if it’s plagiarism but I took the title from Brene Brown’s book because I’m currently really inspired by her. My titles always change though 🤣

I had so much fun with this piece and I think it unlocked a new chapter of my art journey of definitely going bigger with gouache and I seriously can’t wait.

No matter how much color you want to throw down on your painting, your value structure always has to work! Even though I used all kinds of hues in the rocks, I had to adjust them to make sure that when you squint and turn the painting black and white, it still makes sense. This means that if I want to put a cobalt blue in the light area of the rocks for ex, I’ll have to adjust it by making it lighter so it matches the other values of the lighter yellowish greenish hues I have and doesn’t fight or stand out in a way I don’t want to. 

Another thing I (intuitively) did in this painting was to make the area of highest contrast where the wave crashes against the rocks! I hope your eye flows around this painting thru the rhythms in shape and color that I have tried my best to intentionally design.

✨Tip: Claude Monet’s Lily pad paintings are a great example of how to achieve color vibrancy with minimal values! He has so much color in his lily pads but when you turn his paintings black and white, the value structure is so SIMPLE. 

This doesn’t just apply to gouache- it applies to digital paintings as well!

After two brutal days with a total of 8 hours of sleep, I finally got a day where I had NOTHING on my agenda. No meetings, no activities planned. The only mission was to explore and walk around. I can’t tell you how AMAZING that felt, and how I realized how important it is to schedule those days in! Here’s some sketches I got in exploring Capelle Medicee and the piazza by Cattedrale di Santa Maria del Fiore.

The days are long and ppl are out until 11pm or later. Every street corner is filled with fresh smells of gelato, sandwiches, pastries, prosciutto and so much more. I got a month here to explore and I love that I don’t have to rush. Also being able to walk around with one pen and a little sketchbook is incredibly liberating.

I was out until 12am doing some nighttime sketching at the fountain of Neptune in the Piazza della Signoria and along the Arno river is the Ponte Vecchio!

I didn’t wear my glasses so I conveniently couldn’t see 3/4 of the details.

Did some 12am sketching of some  dedicated guitarist gracing the streets by the Arno river. Everything was mostly in shadow and it was fun to play with those subtle values as best I could. 

I think I’ve established for now I’m a vertical hatcher 😆

Did some quick sketching of the alleyway of my Airbnb. There’s always a ton of mopeds?/ motorcycles in this area. On the other side 20 steps up are immediate restaurants as well as a gelateria that always has a long line. I love being able to step out and immediately being in the bustling heartiness. 

During this month, I have one goal. CONSISTENCY. No matter how crappy my sketches turn out (and there’s a-lot I’m not showing) I just keep going. After 3 days of full sketching with 27 sketches so far, I’m already feeling much more at ease! To get better will take more time, but I believe feeling comfortable is so important! It’s amazing how little time it takes to get used to an exercise if you consistently get at it :)

Did a hike up to the lovely Piazzale Michelangelo as well as a visit to the Accademia Gallery to see the famous David statue as well as other beautiful works!! What breathtaking sites on all ends. The view from the piazzale was such a site to digest. Layers of shapes, colors, patterns to create this beautiful tapestry. I will have to come back here to paint. Seeing David up close was quite amazing- the grandness really takes you. I also found his unfinished marble carvings so fascinating. To be able to see the human forms emerge from the rock with the dynamic poses and textures was mind blowing. Swipe to see photos of both places!!

Greetings from Kyoto, Japan! 🇯🇵Justin and I visited Daigo-Ji Temple which was only about 20 min walking from our Airbnb! It was so peaceful there with beautiful luscious greens. I had a wonderful time sketching in Sanboin Garden, the medicine Buddha Yakushi Nyorai in the Kondo, and seeing Goju-no-to, which is a five story pagoda that is the oldest wooden structure in the Kyoto Prefecture! Venturing further we stumbled across the beautiful Bentendo Temple, which felt like a little hidden oasis.

Afterwards we took the bus to visit the famous Higashiyama ward that is one of Kyoto’s best preserved historic districts! I had the most amazing cold miso noodle there with squid ink! This district is also surrounded by beautiful temples that we need to go back and visit in more detail :)

I went to my first ever cat cafe today at a place called Fluffy’s cafe!! Being surrounded by dozens of adorable cats was so therapeutic. Swipe to the 4th pic to find the cutest cat pic of your life. I promise it will make you smile. 🥰 We also enjoyed some delicious food at Nishiki Market! So many options and not enough room in my stomach. The highlights were shrimp tempura, juicy wagu steak, and this new dessert I have never seen or tried until today called a Mont Blanc.. which looks like a ball of hair but is utterly divine. It has a nice subtle chestnut flavor paired with a creamy milk taste and a crumple pastry that all melts in your mouth!

We spent an amazing day in Arashiyama! We did a 1.5 hour boat ride tour down the Hozugawa River, and visited the bamboo grove and the Tenryu-Ji temple which has one of the oldest gardens of the original design in Kyoto! We ended the day visiting the Macaque Monkey park, and let me tell you those monkeys are the cutest animals ever. We got to witness them roaming around minding their own business, eating, nursing, playing, and grooming each other.  They are great to sketch and practice gestures. Swipe to see a mother with her baby- one of the most heartfelt things I’ve seen rather close up!

I visited a temple that is literally right across the street from my Airbnb called Zuishin-in Temple. It’s not so famous among foreign tourists, but is beloved among Japanese people. Legend has it that the most beautiful female poet, the lady Komachi, settled here for the rest of her life. It was so nice to visit a temple with less people and truly enjoy the serenity and silence. 

In my sketches I tried to capture the dappled lighting on the sculptures and monuments scattered throughly the temple grounds. It is quite different to paint dappled light then to sketch it, and definitely a challenge in figuring out shapes!

Throwback Thursday. I was in my third year of college when I was painting like this! Ya. I sucked. I studied animation at USC and the department didn’t have Vis Dev classes or any painting classes, so I was learning on my own. ( I didn’t even know what a Wacom tablet was in high school so safe to say I was a late bloomer). 

 One thing you might not know about me is that after graduation, I worked as an artist on an indie game that never got published and then as a PA ( production assistant) at a production company called Psyop. I just needed a job and I didn’t care if it was waiting on executives. Well soon after on in 2016 .. I got my first break working on Loving Vincent, flew to Poland, and the rest is history. I might not have had a straightforward career path like some artists did working at a studio right away, but I’m grateful for what every opportunity has taught me. 

If you asked me what the top exercises I did to get better, I can narrow it down to: 

✨plein air studies- Building up your observation skills and studying from life should be a life long habit. No plein, no gain. 

✨master studies- I’m always looking at how the masters composed and used colors and I look at more fine artists because there’s something about the old masters that is invaluable. When I find a new artist I love it’s like Christmas. I’d say collecting art books of deceased ( and living) artists is the best investment you can do for your art journey. You never know when you might get a hold of the last copy! 

✨film studies- studying films and how the DOP framed a shot and composed the lighting is invaluable and FUN! Doing value and color studies is a practice that never gets old!

✨Also, go to museums when you can. Nothing beats seeing paintings in person. Nothing.

None of these exercises are mind blowing. But I wanted to get better at color and painting.  It’s about doing them with consistency and being specific with your goals that is the ticket to improvement. Hard work without prioritizing your tasks to meet your goals doesn’t get you anywhere. 

I’m also painfully aware of all my shortcomings and what I need to work on. The journey never ends!! That’s the fun part right?

Trying something new. I am really inspired by Ukrainian artist Arkhyp Kuindzhi right now and I love how bold his value structure is for his paintings. I wanted to see how dark I could push the shadows while still having a sunset mood come across. 

Right now I am starting to teach my students how to take styles and color palettes and adapt them to paintings.. so I am experimenting myself. My goal right now is learning how to change up my workflow to find new results while still being true to myself, and sometimes my intuition says one thing while my brain says another. Every time you push yourself out of your comfort zone it is… UNCOMFORTABLE! But you gotta revel in it a bit or it might defeat you. The biggest thing I learned this far is to have fun with the process! In my opinion, never get too obsessed with a painting. It’s just a painting. Swipe to see my initial color key. People always ask me how I continually hone my color sense and intuition for color. There’s no right or wrong way.. but I can say that continually studying fine artists as well as traditionally painting has helped me ( and will always continue to help me) SO MUCH in being bolder and more experimental with color. 

When I first started my painting Mentorships in 2019, it was with the goal to help students bridge the gap between traditional and digital plein air painting. I wanted to help digital painting students not be so scared of traditional painting and help them unlock the skills of understanding color relationships more. I continue to push and encourage this in my Mentorships, because I think it’s so important to study from life and the fundamentals of color mixing before trying to push anything stylistically! 

Here are three reasons why traditional painting has helped me get better at painting for myself and for work!!

Edgar Payne demo for my mentorship students showing how to build and layer colors in a study with a monochromatic version first! For this study, I chose the color red first to see how I could use more desaturated reds to act as cooler counterparts in the shadows while using more saturated red on other areas as the local color and slight bounce light in fg rocks. I then later added a bit of bluish purples in the shadows and yellow in the rim light.. but 3/4 of this painting is built on one color! 

Working in a monochromatic color scheme can be, in my opinion, a great way to build up your understanding and observation of how colors interact with each other. Why? Because by only using one color and playing with saturated and desaturated versions of that color, you start to see how those more desaturated colors start to take on a life of their own and feel complementary to the original color! I even have some areas that are straight up grays mixed from black and white! But I bet you can’t tell because among all the other colors. They might feel bluish or even a bit green!
